# Project Roadmap

The Open Digital Pathology AI Toolkit aims to develop open, reproducible tools for quantitative histopathology and AI-assisted pathology workflows.

The roadmap is divided into progressive development phases.

---

# Phase 1 — Project Foundation

Establish the core infrastructure of the project.

Goals:

- Create public GitHub repository
- Define project architecture
- Publish documentation
- Recruit collaborators and students
- Define initial computational pathology pipelines

Deliverables:

- repository structure
- documentation
- roadmap
- contribution guidelines

---

# Phase 2 — Histological Image Analysis

Develop initial scripts for quantitative histology analysis.

Planned tools:

### Collagen Analysis

Scripts for analyzing collagen in:

- Picrosirius Red stained slides
- H&E sections
- SHG microscopy

Planned metrics:

- fiber length
- fiber thickness
- fiber orientation
- fiber density
- stromal organization

Applications:

- tumor microenvironment analysis
- stromal remodeling studies
- tumor invasion research

---

# Phase 3 — Tumor Microenvironment Quantification

Develop pipelines to analyze tumor-stroma interactions.

Potential features:

- Tumor Associated Collagen Signatures (TACS)
- tumor budding quantification
- stromal density
- immune cell distribution

These tools aim to support research in:

- oral squamous cell carcinoma
- head and neck cancers
- tumor microenvironment biology

---

# Phase 4 — Immunohistochemistry Analysis

Develop standardized pipelines for digital IHC analysis.

Planned tools:

- automated cell segmentation
- nuclear staining detection
- cytoplasmic staining detection
- H-score calculation
- percentage of positive cells
- staining intensity analysis

Potential applications:

- PD-L1 quantification
- macrophage markers (CD68 / CD163)
- proliferation markers (Ki-67)
- EMT markers

---

# Phase 5 — FISH Signal Detection

Develop tools for automated FISH analysis.

Planned capabilities:

- detection of fused signals
- detection of split signals
- measurement of signal distances
- quantification of positive nuclei

Applications:

- gene rearrangements
- amplification studies
- molecular pathology research

Example targets:

- MAML2
- ALK
- HER2

---

# Phase 6 — AI-assisted Pathology Workflows

Integrate large language models into pathology workflows.

Potential tools:

- pathology report structuring
- extraction of morphological features from text
- differential diagnosis support
- research workflow automation

---

# Phase 7 — Digital Pathology Education

Develop educational tools for pathology training.

Examples:

- AI-assisted diagnostic exercises
- virtual histology cases
- pathology quizzes
- interactive diagnostic reasoning modules

Target users:

- pathology residents
- medical students
- researchers

---

# Phase 8 — Community and Open Science

Expand the project into a collaborative computational pathology platform.

Goals:

- attract contributors
- integrate public pathology datasets
- publish scientific papers
- support open computational pathology research
